column1: Show the names of students who have a grade higher than 5 and have at least 2 friends.
column2: select name from highschooler where grade > 5 intersect select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t2.friend_id having count(*) >= 2
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id where t2.grade > 5 group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 2

column1: What are the names of high schoolers who have a grade of over 5 and have 2 or more friends?
column2: select name from highschooler where grade > 5 intersect select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t2.friend_id having count(*) >= 2
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id where t2.grade > 5 group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 2

column1: What is the average grade of students who have friends?
column2: select avg(t1.grade) from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id
column3: network_1 | select avg(grade) from highschooler where id in (select t1.student_id from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id)

column1: What is the lowest grade of students who do not have any friends?
column2: select grade from highschooler where id not in (select student_id from friend)
column3: network_1 | select min(grade) from highschooler where id not in (select t1.student_id from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id)

column1: Find the average age of the dogs who went through treatments.
column2: select avg(age) from dogs as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id
column3: dog_kennels | select avg(age) from dogs where dog_id in ( select dog_id from treatments )

column1: Which professionals live in the state of Indiana or have done treatment on more than 2 treatments? List his or her id, last name and cell phone.
column2: select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having t1.state = 'Indiana' union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2
column3: dog_kennels | select professional_id, last_name, cell_number from professionals where state = 'Indiana' union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2

column1: Find the id, last name and cell phone of the professionals who live in the state of Indiana or have performed more than two treatments.
column2: select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having t1.state = "Indiana" union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2
column3: dog_kennels | select professional_id, last_name, cell_number from professionals where state = 'Indiana' union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2

column1: Which dogs have not cost their owner more than 1000 for treatment ? List the dog names .
column2: select name from dogs except select t2.name from treatments as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t1.cost_of_treatment > 1000
column3: dog_kennels | select name from dogs where dog_id not in ( select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having sum(cost_of_treatment) > 1000 )

column1: What are the names of the dogs for which the owner has not spend more than 1000 for treatment ?
column2: select name from dogs where dog_id not in (select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having cost_of_treatment > 1000)
column3: dog_kennels | select name from dogs where dog_id not in ( select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having sum(cost_of_treatment) > 1000 )

column1: Which first names are used for professionals or owners but are not used as dog names?
column2: select first_name from professionals union select first_name from owners except select t2.first_name from dogs as t1 join professionals as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.professional_id
column3: dog_kennels | select first_name from professionals union select first_name from owners except select name from dogs

column1: Find the first names that are used for professionals or owners but are not used as dog names.
column2: select first_name from professionals union select first_name from owners except select t2.first_name from dogs as t1 join professionals as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.professional_id
column3: dog_kennels | select first_name from professionals union select first_name from owners except select name from dogs

column1: Tell me the owner id and last name of the owner who spent the most on treatments of his or her dogs.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t3.dog_id = t2.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t3.cost_of_treatment) desc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Which owner has paid the largest amount of money in total for their dogs? Show the owner id and zip code.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t2.charge_amount
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t3.cost_of_treatment) desc limit 1

column1: Find the owner id and zip code of the owner who spent the most money in total for his or her dogs.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t2.cost_of_treatment
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t3.cost_of_treatment) desc limit 1

column1: What are the first name and last name of the professionals who have done treatment with cost below average?
column2: select t2.first_name, t2.last_name from treatments as t1 join professionals as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id where t1.cost_of_treatment < ( select avg(cost_of_treatment) from treatments)
column3: dog_kennels | select distinct t1.first_name, t1.last_name from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 where cost_of_treatment < ( select avg(cost_of_treatment) from treatments )

column1: Which professionals have operated a treatment that costs less than the average? Give me theor first names and last names.
column2: select t2.first_name, t2.last_name from treatments as t1 join professionals as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id where t1.cost_of_treatment < ( select avg(cost_of_treatment) from treatments)
column3: dog_kennels | select distinct t1.first_name, t1.last_name from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 where cost_of_treatment < ( select avg(cost_of_treatment) from treatments )

column1: List the names of the dogs of the rarest breed and the treatment dates of them.
column2: select t2.name, t1.date_of_treatment from treatments as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t2.breed_code = (select breed_code from dogs group by breed_code order by count(*) desc limit 1)
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.name, t2.date_of_treatment from dogs as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t1.breed_code = ( select breed_code from dogs group by breed_code order by count(*) asc limit 1 )

column1: Which dogs are of the rarest breed? Show their names and treatment dates.
column2: select name, date_of_treatment from treatments as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t2.breed_code = (select breed_code from dogs group by breed_code order by count(*) desc limit 1)
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.name, t2.date_of_treatment from dogs as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id where t1.breed_code = ( select breed_code from dogs group by breed_code order by count(*) asc limit 1 )

column1: Which dogs are owned by someone who lives in Virginia? List the owner's first name and the dog's name.
column2: select first_name, last_name from owners where state = 'Virginia'
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.first_name, t2.name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id where t1.state = 'Virginia'

column1: Find the first names of owners living in Virginia and the names of dogs they own.
column2: select first_name, last_name from owners where state = 'Virginia'
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.first_name, t2.name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id where t1.state = 'Virginia'

column1: List the last name of the owner owning the youngest dog.
column2: select t2.last_name from dogs as t1 join owners as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id order by t1.age asc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id where t2.age = ( select max(age) from dogs )

column1: Who owns the youngest dog? Give me his or her last name.
column2: select t2.last_name from dogs as t1 join owners as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id order by t1.age asc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id where t2.age = ( select max(age) from dogs )

column1: Which professionals live in a city containing the substring 'West'? List his or her role, street, city and state.
column2: select first_name, last_name, street, city, state from professionals where city like "%west%"
column3: dog_kennels | select role_code, street, city, state from professionals where city like '%west%'

column1: How much does the most recent treatment cost?
column2: select max(cost_of_treatment) from treatments
column3: dog_kennels | select cost_of_treatment from treatments order by date_of_treatment desc limit 1

column1: How much does the most expensive charge type costs?
column2: select charge_type, max(charge_amount) from charges group by charge_type
column3: dog_kennels | select max(charge_amount) from charges

column1: What are all the possible breed type and size type combinations?
column2: select count(distinct breed_code), count(distinct size_code) from dogs
column3: dog_kennels | select distinct breed_code, size_code from dogs

column1: Show the property type descriptions of properties belonging to that code.
column2: select t1.property_type_description from ref_property_types as t1 join properties as t2 on t1.property_type_code = t2.property_type_code
column3: real_estate_properties | select t2.property_type_description from properties as t1 join ref_property_types as t2 on t1.property_type_code = t2.property_type_code group by t1.property_type_code

column1: What are the names of properties that are either houses or apartments with more than 1 room?
column2: select property_name from properties where property_type_code = "House" or room_count > 1
column3: real_estate_properties | select property_name from properties where property_type_code = "House" union select property_name from properties where property_type_code = "Apartment" and room_count > 1

column1: What is the maximum capacity and the average of all stadiums ?
column2: select max(capacity), avg(average) from stadium
column3: concert_singer | select max(capacity), average from stadium

column1: Show the name and theme for all concerts and the number of singers in each concert.
column2: select concert_name, theme, count(*) from concert group by theme
column3: concert_singer | select t2.concert_name, t2.theme, count(*) from singer_in_concert as t1 join concert as t2 on t1.concert_id = t2.concert_id group by t2.concert_id

column1: What are the names , themes , and number of singers for every concert ?
column2: select t3.concert_name, t2.theme, count(*) from concert as t1 join singer_in_concert as t2 on t1.concert_id = t2.concert_id join singer as t3 on t1.song_id = t3.song_id group by t1.concert_id
column3: concert_singer | select t2.concert_name, t2.theme, count(*) from singer_in_concert as t1 join concert as t2 on t1.concert_id = t2.concert_id group by t2.concert_id

column1: List singer names and number of concerts for each singer.
column2: select t2.name, count(*) from concert as t1 join singer as t2 on t1.song_id = t2.song_id group by t1.song_id
column3: concert_singer | select t2.name, count(*) from singer_in_concert as t1 join singer as t2 on t1.singer_id = t2.singer_id group by t2.singer_id

column1: What are the names of the singers and number of concerts for each person?
column2: select t2.name, count(*) from concert as t1 join singer as t2 on t1.song_id = t2.song_id group by t1.song_id
column3: concert_singer | select t2.name, count(*) from singer_in_concert as t1 join singer as t2 on t1.singer_id = t2.singer_id group by t2.singer_id

column1: List all singer names in concerts in year 2014.
column2: select t3.name from concert as t1 join singer_in_concert as t2 on t1.concert_id = t2.concert_id join singer as t3 on t2.song_id = t3.song_id where t1.year = 2014
column3: concert_singer | select t2.name from singer_in_concert as t1 join singer as t2 on t1.singer_id = t2.singer_id join concert as t3 on t1.concert_id = t3.concert_id where t3.year = 2014

column1: What are the names of the singers who performed in a concert in 2014?
column2: select t3.name from concert as t1 join singer_in_concert as t2 on t1.concert_id = t2.concert_id join singer as t3 on t2.song_id = t3.song_id where t1.year = 2014
column3: concert_singer | select t2.name from singer_in_concert as t1 join singer as t2 on t1.singer_id = t2.singer_id join concert as t3 on t1.concert_id = t3.concert_id where t3.year = 2014

column1: Find the weight of the youngest dog.

column3: pets_1 | select count(*) from student as t1 join has_pet as t2 on t1.stuid = t2.stuid join pets as t3 on t2.petid = t3.petid where t1.sex = 'F' and t3.pettype = 'dog'

column1: Find the first name of students who have both cat and dog pets .

column1: Find the id of students who do not have a cat pet.

column1: How many countries does each continent have? List the continent id, continent name and the number of countries.

column3: car_1 | select t1.contid, t1.continent, count(*) from continents as t1 join countries as t2 on t1.contid = t2.continent group by t1.contid;

column1: For each continent, list its id, name, and how many countries it has?

column3: car_1 | select t1.fullname, t1.id, count(*) from car_makers as t1 join model_list as t2 on t1.id = t2.maker group by t1.id;

column3: car_1 | select t1.model from car_names as t1 join cars_data as t2 on t1.makeid = t2.id order by t2.horsepower asc limit 1;

column3: car_1 | select t1.model from car_names as t1 join cars_data as t2 on t1.makeid = t2.id order by t2.horsepower asc limit 1;

column1: Find the model of the car whose weight is below the average weight.

column3: car_1 | select t1.model from car_names as t1 join cars_data as t2 on t1.makeid = t2.id where t2.weight < (select avg(weight) from cars_data)

column1: What is the model for the car with a weight smaller than the average?

column2: select count(*) from airports as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.airport = t2.sourceairport where t1.city = "Ashley" and t1.airportcode = "Aberdeen"
column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.destairport = t2.airportcode join airports as t3 on t1.sourceairport = t3.airportcode where t2.city = "Ashley" and t3.city = "Aberdeen"

column1: How many flights does airline 'JetBlue Airways' have?

column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from flights as t1 join airlines as t2 on t1.airline = t2.uid where t2.airline = "JetBlue Airways"

column1: Give the number of Jetblue Airways flights.

column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from flights as t1 join airlines as t2 on t1.airline = t2.uid where t2.airline = "JetBlue Airways"

column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t2.airline = t1.uid where t1.airline = "United Airlines" and t2.destairport = "ASY"

column1: How many United Airlines flights go to City 'Aberdeen'?
column2: select count(*) from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t1.city = 'Aberdeen'
column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.destairport = t2.airportcode join airlines as t3 on t3.uid = t1.airline where t2.city = "Aberdeen" and t3.airline = "United Airlines"

column1: Count the number of United Airlines flights that arrive in Aberdeen.

column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.destairport = t2.airportcode join airlines as t3 on t3.uid = t1.airline where t2.city = "Aberdeen" and t3.airline = "United Airlines"

column1: Which city is the most frequent source airport?
column2: select t1.city from airports as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.airport = t2.sourceairport group by t1.city order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: flight_2 | select t1.city from airports as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.airportcode = t2.sourceairport group by t1.city order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: What is the airport code of the airport with the most flights?
column2: select airportcode from flights group by airportcode order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airportcode from airports as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.airportcode = t2.destairport or t1.airportcode = t2.sourceairport group by t1.airportcode order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Give the code of the airport with the least flights.

column3: flight_2 | select t1.airportcode from airports as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.airportcode = t2.destairport or t1.airportcode = t2.sourceairport group by t1.airportcode order by count(*) limit 1

column1: Find the abbreviation and country of the airline that has fewest number of flights?

column3: flight_2 | select t1.abbreviation, t1.country from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline order by count(*) limit 1

column1: What is the abbreviation of the airilne has the fewest flights and what country is it in?

column3: flight_2 | select t1.abbreviation, t1.country from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline order by count(*) limit 1

column1: Which airlines have a flight with source airport AHD?
column2: select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.uid where t2.sourceairport = "AHD"
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "AHD"

column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.destairport = "AHD"

column1: Which airlines have a flight with destination airport AHD?
column2: select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.uid where t2.sourceairport = "AHD"
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.destairport = "AHD"

column1: Find all airlines that have flights from both airports 'APG' and 'CVO'.
column2: select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.uid where t2.sourceairport = 'APG' intersect select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.uid where t2.sourceairport = 'CVO'
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "APG" intersect select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "CVO"

column1: Which airlines have departing flights from both APG and CVO airports?
column2: select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.uid where t2.sourceairport = 'APG' intersect select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.uid where t2.sourceairport = 'CVO'
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "APG" intersect select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "CVO"

column1: Find all airlines that have flights from airport 'CVO' but not from 'APG'.
column2: select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.uid where t2.sourceairport = 'CVO' except select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airport where t2.sourceairport = 'APG'
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "CVO" except select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "APG"

column1: Which airlines have departures from CVO but not from APG airports?
column2: select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.uid where t2.sourceairport = 'CVO' except select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airportcode where t2.sourceairport = 'APG'
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "CVO" except select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline where t2.sourceairport = "APG"

column1: Find all airlines that have fewer than 200 flights.

column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline having count(*) < 200

column1: Which airlines have less than 200 flights?
column2: select airline from flights group by airline having count(*) < 200
column3: flight_2 | select t1.airline from airlines as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.uid = t2.airline group by t1.airline having count(*) < 200

column1: What are flight numbers of Airline "United Airlines"?

column3: flight_2 | select t1.flightno from flights as t1 join airlines as t2 on t2.uid = t1.airline where t2.airline = "United Airlines"

column3: flight_2 | select t1.flightno from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.sourceairport = t2.airportcode where t2.city = "Aberdeen"

column1: What are flight numbers of flights arriving at City "Aberdeen"?
column2: select distinct t1.flightno from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.sourceairport = t2.airport where t2.city = "Aberdeen"
column3: flight_2 | select t1.flightno from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.destairport = t2.airportcode where t2.city = "Aberdeen"

column1: Give the flight numbers of flights arriving in Aberdeen.

column3: flight_2 | select t1.flightno from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.destairport = t2.airportcode where t2.city = "Aberdeen"

column3: flight_2 | select count(*) from flights as t1 join airports as t2 on t1.destairport = t2.airportcode where t2.city = "Aberdeen" or t2.city = "Abilene"

column1: Find the name of airports which do not have any flight in and out.
column2: select airportname from airports where airportcode not in (select sourceairport from airports)
column3: flight_2 | select airportname from airports where airportcode not in (select sourceairport from flights union select destairport from flights)

column1: Which airports do not have departing or arriving flights?
column2: select airportname from airports except select t1.airportname from airports as t1 join flights as t2 on t1.airportcode = t2.sourceairport
column3: flight_2 | select airportname from airports where airportcode not in (select sourceairport from flights union select destairport from flights)

column1: Find the manager name and district of the shop whose number of products is the largest.

column3: employee_hire_evaluation | select manager_name, district from shop order by number_products desc limit 1

column1: What are the manager name and district of the shop that sells the largest number of products?

column3: employee_hire_evaluation | select manager_name, district from shop order by number_products desc limit 1

column1: For each shop, return the number of employees working there and the name of the shop.

column3: employee_hire_evaluation | select count(*), t2.name from hiring as t1 join shop as t2 on t1.shop_id = t2.shop_id group by t2.name

column1: What are the paragraph texts for the document with the name 'Customer reviews'?

column3: cre_Doc_Template_Mgt | select t1.paragraph_text from paragraphs as t1 join documents as t2 on t1.document_id = t2.document_id where t2.document_name = "Customer reviews"

column1: What are the names of the teachers whose hometown is not `` Little Lever Urban District '' ?

column3: course_teach | select name from teacher where hometown!= "little lever urban district"

column1: Show names of teachers and the courses they are arranged to teach.

column3: course_teach | select t3.name, t2.course from course_arrange as t1 join course as t2 on t1.course_id = t2.course_id join teacher as t3 on t1.teacher_id = t3.teacher_id

column1: Show names of teachers and the courses they are arranged to teach in ascending alphabetical order of the teacher's name.

column1: What is the average age of the visitors whose membership level is not higher than 4?
column2: select avg(age) from visitor where level_of_membership imobilizes 4
column3: museum_visit | select avg(age) from visitor where level_of_membership <= 4

column1: Find the id and name of the museum that has the most staff members?
column2: select t1.museum_id, t1.name from museum as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.museum_id = t2.id group by t1.museum_id order by sum(num_of_staff) desc limit 1
column3: museum_visit | select museum_id, name from museum order by num_of_staff desc limit 1

column1: What are the id, name and membership level of visitors who have spent the largest amount of money in total in all museum tickets?
column2: select t1.id, t1.name, t1.level_of_membership from visitor as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.id = t2.visitor_id order by sum(t2.total_spent) desc limit 1
column3: museum_visit | select t2.visitor_id, t1.name, t1.level_of_membership from visitor as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.id = t2.visitor_id group by t2.visitor_id order by sum(t2.total_spent) desc limit 1

column1: What is the total ticket expense of the visitors whose membership level is 1?
column2: select sum(total_spent) from visit as t1 join visitor as t2 on t1.visit_id = t2.id where t2.level_of_membership = 1
column3: museum_visit | select sum(t2.total_spent) from visitor as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.id = t2.visitor_id where t1.level_of_membership = 1

column1: What is the name of the visitor who visited both a museum opened before 2009 and a museum opened after 2011?
column2: select t3.name from museum as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.museum_id = t2.museum_id join visitor as t3 on t2.visit = t3.id where t1.open_year < 2009 intersect select t3.name from museum as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.museum_id = t2.museum_id where t1.open_year > 2011
column3: museum_visit | select t1.name from visitor as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.id = t2.visitor_id join museum as t3 on t3.museum_id = t2.museum_id where t3.open_year < 2009 intersect select t1.name from visitor as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.id = t2.visitor_id join museum as t3 on t3.museum_id = t2.museum_id where t3.open_year > 2011

column1: Find the number of visitors who did not visit any museum opened after 2010.
column2: select count(*) from visitor where id not in ( select visitor_id from visit where open_year > 2010 )
column3: museum_visit | select count(*) from visitor where id not in (select t2.visitor_id from museum as t1 join visit as t2 on t1.museum_id = t2.museum_id where t1.open_year > 2010)

column1: Find the highest rank of losers in all matches.
column2: select max(loser_rank) from matches
column3: wta_1 | select min(loser_rank) from matches

column1: What is the best rank of losers across all matches?
column2: select best_of from matches as t1 join loser_rank as t2 on t1.loser_id = t2.loser_id group by t1.loser_rank order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: wta_1 | select min(loser_rank) from matches

column1: Find the name of tourney that has more than 10 matches.

column3: wta_1 | select tourney_name from matches group by tourney_name having count(*) > 10

column1: What are the names of tournaments that have more than 10 matches?

column3: wta_1 | select tourney_name from matches group by tourney_name having count(*) > 10

column1: What are the names of players who won in both 2013 and 2016?
column2: select t1.winner_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.year = 2013 intersect select t1.winner_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.year = 2016
column3: wta_1 | select winner_name from matches where year = 2013 intersect select winner_name from matches where year = 2016

column1: What are the country code and first name of the players who won in both tourney WTA Championships and Australian Open?
column2: select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.turner_name = 'WTA Championships' intersect select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.turner_name = 'Australian Open'
column3: wta_1 | select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = 'WTA Championships' intersect select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = 'Australian Open'

column1: What are the first names and country codes for players who won both the WTA Championships and the Australian Open?
column2: select t1.first_name, t1.country_code from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.turner_name = 'WTA Championships' intersect select t1.first_name, t1.country_code from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.player_id where t2.turner_name = 'Australian Open'
column3: wta_1 | select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = 'WTA Championships' intersect select t1.country_code, t1.first_name from players as t1 join matches as t2 on t1.player_id = t2.winner_id where t2.tourney_name = 'Australian Open'

column1: Find the first name and country code of the oldest player.

column3: wta_1 | select first_name, country_code from players order by birth_date limit 1

column1: What is the first name and country code of the oldest player?

column1: What is maximum and minimum death toll caused each time?

column3: battle_death | select max(killed), min(killed) from death

column1: What is the average number of injuries caused each time?

column3: battle_death | select avg(injured) from death

column2: select killed, injured from death where ship_id in (select caused_by_ship_id from ship where tonnage = 't')
column3: battle_death | select t1.killed, t1.injured from death as t1 join ship as t2 on t1.caused_by_ship_id = t2.id where t2.tonnage = 't'

column1: What are the ids and names of the battles that led to more than 10 people killed in total.
column2: select t1.id, t1.name from battle as t1 join death as t2 on t1.id = t2.caused_by_ship_id group by t1.id having sum(t2.killed) > 10

column1: What is the ship id and name that caused most total injuries?

column3: battle_death | select t2.id, t2.name from death as t1 join ship as t2 on t1.caused_by_ship_id = t2.id group by t2.id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Find the semester when both Master students and Bachelor students got enrolled in.

column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select distinct t2.semester_id from degree_programs as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.degree_program_id = t2.degree_program_id where degree_summary_name = 'Master' intersect select distinct t2.semester_id from degree_programs as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.degree_program_id = t2.degree_program_id where degree_summary_name = 'Bachelor'

column3: student_transcripts_tracking | select distinct t2.semester_id from degree_programs as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.degree_program_id = t2.degree_program_id where degree_summary_name = 'Master' intersect select distinct t2.semester_id from degree_programs as t1 join student_enrolment as t2 on t1.degree_program_id = t2.degree_program_id where degree_summary_name = 'Bachelor'

column3: world_1 | select name from country where continent = "Africa" and population < (select min(population) from country where continent = "Asia")

column1: Which Asian countries have a population that is larger than any country in Africa?
column2: select name from country where population > (select max(population) from country where continent = 'Asia')
column3: world_1 | select name from country where continent = "Asia" and population > (select max(population) from country where continent = "Africa")

column1: What are the Asian countries which have a population larger than that of any country in Africa?
column2: select name from country where population > (select min(population) from country where continent = 'Asia')
column3: world_1 | select name from country where continent = "Asia" and population > (select min(population) from country where continent = "Africa")

column1: What are the country codes for countries that do not speak English?
column2: select countrycode from country where language!= "English"
column3: world_1 | select countrycode from countrylanguage except select countrycode from countrylanguage where language = "English"

column1: Return the country codes for countries that do not speak English.
column2: select countrycode from country where language!= "English"
column3: world_1 | select countrycode from countrylanguage except select countrycode from countrylanguage where language = "English"

column1: What are the codes of the countries that do not speak English and whose government forms are not Republic?
column2: select countrycode from country where language!= "English" and governmentform!= "Republic"
column3: world_1 | select code from country where governmentform!= "Republic" except select countrycode from countrylanguage where language = "English"

column1: Return the codes of countries that do not speak English and do not have Republics for governments.
column2: select countrycode from country where language!= "English" and governmentform!= "Republic"
column3: world_1 | select code from country where governmentform!= "Republic" except select countrycode from countrylanguage where language = "English"

column1: Which cities are in European countries where English is not the official language?
column2: select t1.name from city as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.countrycode = t2.countrycode where t2.language!= "English"
column3: world_1 | select distinct t2.name from country as t1 join city as t2 on t2.countrycode = t1.code where t1.continent = 'Europe' and t1.name not in (select t3.name from country as t3 join countrylanguage as t4 on t3.code = t4.countrycode where t4.isofficial = 'T' and t4.language = 'English')

column1: What are the names of cities in Europe for which English is not the official language?
column2: select name from country where continent = "Europe" and language!= "English"
column3: world_1 | select distinct t2.name from country as t1 join city as t2 on t2.countrycode = t1.code where t1.continent = 'Europe' and t1.name not in (select t3.name from country as t3 join countrylanguage as t4 on t3.code = t4.countrycode where t4.isofficial = 'T' and t4.language = 'English')

column1: Which unique cities are in Asian countries where Chinese is the official language ?
column2: select distinct t1.name from city as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.countrycode = t2.countrycode where t2.language = "Chinese"
column3: world_1 | select distinct t3.name from country as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.code = t2.countrycode join city as t3 on t1.code = t3.countrycode where t2.isofficial = 't' and t2.language = 'chinese' and t1.continent = "asia"

column1: Return the different names of cities that are in Asia and for which Chinese is the official language.
column2: select distinct t1.name from city as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.countrycode = t2.countrycode where t2.continent = "Asia" and t2.language = "Chinese"
column3: world_1 | select distinct t3.name from country as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.code = t2.countrycode join city as t3 on t1.code = t3.countrycode where t2.isofficial = 'T' and t2.language = 'Chinese' and t1.continent = "Asia"

column1: Return the country name and the numbers of languages spoken for each country that speaks at least 3 languages.
column2: select t1.name, count(*), t1.code from country as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.countrycode = t2.countrycode group by t1.name having count(*) >= 3
column3: world_1 | select count(t2.language), t1.name from country as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.code = t2.countrycode group by t1.name having count(*) > 2

column1: What are the names of countries that speak more than 2 languages, as well as how many languages they speak?
column2: select t1.name, count(*) from country as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.countrycode = t2.countrycode group by t1.name having count(*) > 2
column3: world_1 | select count(t2.language), t1.name from country as t1 join countrylanguage as t2 on t1.code = t2.countrycode group by t1.name having count(*) > 2

column1: Find the government form name and total population for each government form whose average life expectancy is longer than 72.
column2: select governmentform, sum(population) from country where lifeexpectancy > 72 group by governmentform
column3: world_1 | select sum(population), governmentform from country group by governmentform having avg(lifeexpectancy) > 72

column1: What are the different government forms and what is the total population of each for government forms that have an average life expectancy greater than 72?
column2: select sum(population), governmentform from country where lifeexpectancy > 72 group by governmentform
column3: world_1 | select sum(population), governmentform from country group by governmentform having avg(lifeexpectancy) > 72

column1: Find the average life expectancy and total population for each continent where the average life expectancy is shorter than 72?
column2: select avg(lifeexpectancy), sum(population), continent from country where avg(lifeexpectancy) < 72 group by continent
column3: world_1 | select sum(population), avg(lifeexpectancy), continent from country group by continent having avg(lifeexpectancy) < 72

column1: What are the different continents and the total popuation and average life expectancy corresponding to each, for continents that have an average life expectancy less than 72?
column2: select continent, sum(population), avg(lifeexpectancy) from country where population < 72 group by continent
column3: world_1 | select sum(population), avg(lifeexpectancy), continent from country group by continent having avg(lifeexpectancy) < 72

column1: Return the names and surface areas of the 5 largest countries.
column2: select name, surfacearea from country order by population desc limit 5
column3: world_1 | select name, surfacearea from country order by surfacearea desc limit 5

column1: What is the total population and average area of countries in the continent of North America whose area is bigger than 3000 ?
column2: select sum(population), avg(surfacearea) from country where continent = "North America" and region > 3000
column3: world_1 | select sum(population), avg(surfacearea) from country where continent = "north america" and surfacearea > 3000

column1: Give the total population and average surface area corresponding to countries in North America that have a surface area greater than 3000 .
column2: select sum(population), avg(surfacearea) from country where region = "North America" and surfacearea > 3000
column3: world_1 | select sum(population), avg(surfacearea) from country where continent = "north america" and surfacearea > 3000

column1: What is the language spoken by the largest percentage of people in each country?
column2: select language, count(*) from countrylanguage group by language order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: world_1 | select language, countrycode, max(percentage) from countrylanguage group by countrycode

column1: What are the country codes of the different countries, and what are the languages spoken by the greatest percentage of people for each?
column2: select countrycode, language from countrylanguage group by countrycode order by sum(population) desc limit 1
column3: world_1 | select language, countrycode, max(percentage) from countrylanguage group by countrycode

column1: What is the total number of countries where Spanish is spoken by the largest percentage of people?
column2: select count(*) from countrylanguage where language = 'Spanish' group by countrycode order by sum(population) desc limit 1
column3: world_1 | select count(*), max(percentage) from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode

column1: Count the number of countries for which Spanish is the predominantly spoken language.
column2: select count(*) from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: world_1 | select count(*), max(percentage) from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode

column1: What are the codes of countries where Spanish is spoken by the largest percentage of people?
column2: select countrycode from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode order by sum(population) desc limit 1
column3: world_1 | select countrycode, max(percentage) from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode

column1: Return the codes of countries for which Spanish is the predominantly spoken language.
column2: select countrycode from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: world_1 | select countrycode, max(percentage) from countrylanguage where language = "Spanish" group by countrycode

column1: Show the names of conductors and the orchestras they have conducted.
column2: select t2.name, t3.orchestral_name from conductor as t1 join orchestra as t2 on t1.director_id = t2.director_id join performance as t3 on t2.performance_id = t3.performance_id
column3: orchestra | select t1.name, t2.orchestra from conductor as t1 join orchestra as t2 on t1.conductor_id = t2.conductor_id

column1: What are the names of conductors as well as the corresonding orchestras that they have conducted?
column2: select t2.name, t3.orchestral_name from orchestra as t1 join conductor as t2 on t1.orchestral_id = t2.orchestral_id join orchestra as t3 on t1.orchestral_id = t3.orchestral_id
column3: orchestra | select t1.name, t2.orchestra from conductor as t1 join orchestra as t2 on t1.conductor_id = t2.conductor_id

column1: What is the name of the conductor who has conducted the most orchestras?
column2: select t1.name from conductor as t1 join orchestra as t2 on t1. conductor_id = t2. conductor_id group by t1.name order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: orchestra | select t1.name from conductor as t1 join orchestra as t2 on t1.conductor_id = t2.conductor_id group by t2.conductor_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Please show the record formats of orchestras in ascending order of count.
column2: select major_record_format from orchestra order by count(*) asc
column3: orchestra | select major_record_format from orchestra group by major_record_format order by count(*) asc

column1: What are the orchestras that do not have any performances?
column2: select orchestra from orchestra except select orchestra from performance
column3: orchestra | select orchestra from orchestra where orchestra_id not in (select orchestra_id from performance)

column1: Show the years in which orchestras that have given more than one performance are founded.
column2: select t1.year_of_founded from orchestra as t1 join performance as t2 on t1.orchester_id = t2.orchester_id group by t1.orchester_id having count(*) > 1
column3: orchestra | select year_of_founded from orchestra as t1 join performance as t2 on t1.orchestra_id = t2.orchestra_id group by t2.orchestra_id having count(*) > 1

column1: What are years of founding for orchestras that have had more than a single performance?
column2: select year_of_founded from orchestra group by year_of_founded having count(*) > 1
column3: orchestra | select year_of_founded from orchestra as t1 join performance as t2 on t1.orchestra_id = t2.orchestra_id group by t2.orchestra_id having count(*) > 1

column1: Return the grade for the high schooler named Kyle.
column2: select distinct t2.grade from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id where t1.name = "Kyle"
column3: network_1 | select grade from highschooler where name = "Kyle"

column1: What is Kyle's id?
column2: select Kyle from highschooler where name = 'Kyle'
column3: network_1 | select id from highschooler where name = "Kyle"

column1: How many friends does each student have?
column2: select count(distinct friend_id) from friend
column3: network_1 | select student_id, count(*) from friend group by student_id

column1: Show the names of high school students and their corresponding number of friends.
column2: select t1.name, count(*) from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t1.id
column3: network_1 | select t2.name, count(*) from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id

column1: What are the names of the high schoolers and how many friends does each have?
column2: select count(*), t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t1.id
column3: network_1 | select t2.name, count(*) from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id

column1: What is the name of the high schooler who has the greatest number of friends?
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t1.id order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Show the names of high schoolers who have at least 3 friends.
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t2.friend_id having count(*) >= 3
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 3

column1: What are the names of high schoolers who have 3 or more friends?
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t2.friend_id having count(*) >= 3
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 3

column1: Show the names of all of the high schooler Kyle's friends.
column2: select distinct t2.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id where t1.name = "Kyle"
column3: network_1 | select t3.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id join highschooler as t3 on t1.friend_id = t3.id where t2.name = "Kyle"

column1: Return the names of friends of the high school student Kyle.
column2: select t2.friend_id from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id where t1.name = "Kyle"
column3: network_1 | select t3.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id join highschooler as t3 on t1.friend_id = t3.id where t2.name = "Kyle"

column1: Count the number of friends Kyle has.
column2: select count(distinct friend_id) from highschooler where name = 'Kyle'
column3: network_1 | select count(*) from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id where t2.name = "Kyle"

column1: Show ids of all students who do not have any friends.
column2: select student_id from student except select student_id from friend
column3: network_1 | select id from highschooler except select student_id from friend

column1: What are the ids of high school students who do not have friends?
column2: select id from highschooler except select friend_id from friend
column3: network_1 | select id from highschooler except select student_id from friend

column1: What are the names of students who have no friends?
column2: select name from student where student_id not in (select student_id from friend)
column3: network_1 | select name from highschooler except select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id

column1: What are the ids of students who both have friends and are liked?
column2: select t1.student_id from friend as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.friend_id = t2.student_id
column3: network_1 | select student_id from friend intersect select liked_id from likes

column1: Show name of all students who have some friends and also are liked by someone else.
column2: select t1.name from student as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.liked_id join friend as t3 on t1.student_id = t3.student_id intersect select t1.name from student as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id intersect select t2.name from likes as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.liked_id = t2.id

column1: Show the names of high schoolers who have likes, and numbers of likes for each.
column2: select t1.name, count(*) from highschooler as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.liked_id group by t1.id
column3: network_1 | select t2.name, count(*) from likes as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id

column1: What are the names of high schoolers who have likes, and how many likes does each have?
column2: select t1.name, count(*) from highschooler as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.liked_id group by t1.id
column3: network_1 | select t2.name, count(*) from likes as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id

column1: What is the name of the high schooler who has the greatest number of likes?
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.liked_id group by t2.name order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from likes as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Show the names of students who have at least 2 likes.
column2: select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join likes as t2 on t1.id = t2.student_id group by t1.name having count(*) >= 2
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from likes as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 2

column1: Show the names of students who have a grade higher than 5 and have at least 2 friends.
column2: select name from highschooler where grade > 5 intersect select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t1.name having count(*) >= 2
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id where t2.grade > 5 group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 2

column1: What are the names of high schoolers who have a grade of over 5 and have 2 or more friends?
column2: select name from highschooler where grade > 5 intersect select t1.name from highschooler as t1 join friend as t2 on t1.id = t2.friend_id group by t2.friend_id having count(*) >= 2
column3: network_1 | select t2.name from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id where t2.grade > 5 group by t1.student_id having count(*) >= 2

column1: Find the average grade of all students who have some friends.
column2: select avg(t2.grade) from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id group by t1.student_id
column3: network_1 | select avg(grade) from highschooler where id in (select t1.student_id from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id)

column1: What is the average grade of students who have friends?
column2: select avg(t2.grade) from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id
column3: network_1 | select avg(grade) from highschooler where id in (select t1.student_id from friend as t1 join highschooler as t2 on t1.student_id = t2.id)

column1: Which states have both owners and professionals living there?
column2: select state from owners union select state from professionals
column3: dog_kennels | select state from owners intersect select state from professionals

column1: What is the average age of the dogs who have gone through any treatments?
column2: select avg(age) from dogs as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id
column3: dog_kennels | select avg(age) from dogs where dog_id in ( select dog_id from treatments )

column1: Find the average age of the dogs who went through treatments.
column2: select avg(age) from dogs as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.dog_id = t2.dog_id
column3: dog_kennels | select avg(age) from dogs where dog_id in ( select dog_id from treatments )

column1: Which professionals live in the state of Indiana or have done treatment on more than 2 treatments? List his or her id, last name and cell phone.
column2: select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id where t1.state = "Indiana" group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2
column3: dog_kennels | select professional_id, last_name, cell_number from professionals where state = 'Indiana' union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2

column1: Find the id, last name and cell phone of the professionals who live in the state of Indiana or have performed more than two treatments.
column2: select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.home_phone from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id where t1.state = "Indiana" group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2
column3: dog_kennels | select professional_id, last_name, cell_number from professionals where state = 'Indiana' union select t1.professional_id, t1.last_name, t1.cell_number from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) > 2

column1: Which dogs have not cost their owner more than 1000 for treatment ? List the dog names .
column2: select name from dogs where dog_id not in (select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having cost_of_treatment > 1000)
column3: dog_kennels | select name from dogs where dog_id not in ( select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having sum(cost_of_treatment) > 1000 )

column1: What are the names of the dogs for which the owner has not spend more than 1000 for treatment ?
column2: select name from dogs where owner_id not in (select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having cost_of_treatment > 1000)
column3: dog_kennels | select name from dogs where dog_id not in ( select dog_id from treatments group by dog_id having sum(cost_of_treatment) > 1000 )

column1: Which first names are used for professionals or owners but are not used as dog names?
column2: select first_name from professionals union select last_name from dogs
column3: dog_kennels | select first_name from professionals union select first_name from owners except select name from dogs

column1: Find the first names that are used for professionals or owners but are not used as dog names.
column2: select first_name from professionals union select last_name from dogs
column3: dog_kennels | select first_name from professionals union select first_name from owners except select name from dogs

column1: Which professional did not operate any treatment on dogs? List the professional's id, role and email.
column2: select professional_id, role_code, email_address from professionals except select t1.professional_id, t1.role_code from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id where t2.dog_id = 1
column3: dog_kennels | select professional_id, role_code, email_address from professionals except select t1.professional_id, t1.role_code, t1.email_address from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id

column1: Give me the id, role and email of the professionals who did not perform any treatment on dogs.
column2: select professional_id, role_code, email_address from professionals except select t1.professional_id, t2.role_code from treatments as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.treatment_id = t2.treatment_id
column3: dog_kennels | select professional_id, role_code, email_address from professionals except select t1.professional_id, t1.role_code, t1.email_address from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id

column1: Which owner has paid for the most treatments on his or her dogs? List the owner id and last name.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.last_name from owners as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id group by t1.owner_id order by count(*) desc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: Tell me the owner id and last name of the owner who spent the most on treatments of his or her dogs.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.last_name from owners as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t2.cost_of_treatment) desc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.last_name from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by count(*) desc limit 1

column1: What is the description of the treatment type that costs the least money in total?
column2: select t1.treatment_type_description from treatment_types as t1 join charges as t2 on t1.treatment_type_code = t2.treatment_type_code group by t1.treatment_type_code order by sum(t2.cost_of_treatment) asc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.treatment_type_description from treatment_types as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.treatment_type_code = t2.treatment_type_code group by t1.treatment_type_code order by sum(cost_of_treatment) asc limit 1

column1: Which owner has paid the largest amount of money in total for their dogs? Show the owner id and zip code.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join charges as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t2.charge_amount) desc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t3.cost_of_treatment) desc limit 1

column1: Find the owner id and zip code of the owner who spent the most money in total for his or her dogs.
column2: select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join charges as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t2.charge_amount) desc limit 1
column3: dog_kennels | select t1.owner_id, t1.zip_code from owners as t1 join dogs as t2 on t1.owner_id = t2.owner_id join treatments as t3 on t2.dog_id = t3.dog_id group by t1.owner_id order by sum(t3.cost_of_treatment) desc limit 1

column1: Find the id and cell phone of the professionals who operate two or more types of treatments.
column2: select t1.professional_id, t1.home_phone from professionals as t1 join treatments as t2 on t1.professional_id = t2.professional_id group by t1.professional_id having count(*) >= 2
